  "prompt": "Why did oil prices fall again in 2015?",
  "response": "Oil prices fell significantly in 2015 due to a combination of factors:\n\n1. **Supply and Demand Imbalance**: There was an oversupply of oil in the market, primarily due to increased production in the United States. The U.S. had become the largest oil producer in the world, thanks to the shale oil boom, leading to a significant rise in output.\n\n2. **OPEC's Decision**: The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), particularly Saudi Arabia, decided to maintain high production levels instead of cutting output to stabilize prices. Their strategy was to protect market share and curb the rising U.S. shale production.\n\n3. **Slowing Global Demand**: Economic slowdowns in major markets, particularly in China, resulted in reduced demand for oil. China's economy showed signs of deceleration, impacting projections for oil consumption.\n\n4. **Strong U.S. Dollar**: The strengthening of the U.S. dollar made oil more expensive for holders of other currencies, leading to reduced demand in international markets.\n\n5. **Speculative Trading**: Market speculation also played a role in driving prices lower, as traders reacted to supply forecasts and geopolitical factors.\n\nThese combined factors culminated in a significant drop in oil prices throughout 2015, with West Texas Intermediate (WTI) crude oil prices falling from over $100 per barrel in mid-2014 to around $30 per barrel by early 2016.",
